            <h2 class="page-header">Rock climbing is not a sport, it is a way of life</h2>

            <p>I have been climbing since 1974, when I started climbing with the Boy Scouts in England.  Back then climbing
            was an exclusive club.  There was no sticky rubber, harnesses or commercial protection devices.  Before you started leading
            you had to apprentice for years with a skilled leader, and the leader never fell.  If the leader fell, there was a good chance 
            of serious injury or death.  How could you not be attracted to the sport?</p>

            <p>I was lucky enough to meet a Scout Leader who formed a small group to go hiking and climbing on the weekends.  I was
            hooked to climbing instantly, and before long I was itching to travel and climb around the world.  It took a while to
            realise my dream, but I have been lucky enough to have managed to fullful my dream, in fact I am still living it.</p>
